<br>
here's my perspective on the whole thing. <br>
<br>
something that seems to have slipped through the cracks in the discussion so far is the United States' obsession with college degrees. people who have degrees nearly automatically make more money than those who are just ordinary smart people. <br>
<br>
take my dad for instance. he used to work for a company that did programming and design for NASA (among other things). my dad was their computer support tech. he fixed their printers, replaced monitors, etc. but he was also capable of figuring out how to solve hardware/software conflicts that the PhD's in his office couldn't fix. and they were programmers and engineers. however, they made three times as much because my dad has no college degree. his boss said they couldn't pay him any more unless he got a BA. <br>
<br>
a lot of people can't afford college and even if they are smart, even if they have a decent job they will not be able to make as much money without a degree. maybe this happens in other places in the world too (having only lived in the U.S. i wouldn't know) but it happens a lot here. <br>
<br>
so, back to taxes. part of the problem with the rich is that whole 'charitable contribution' thing. it's a nice idea but in reality it doesn't work very well. rich people can donate money to charities and then they don't have to pay taxes. (i think you have to donate amounts that are equal to the amount you would normally pay in taxes, but i'm not one hundred percent certain.) then the government has to raise taxes on the rest of the population to continue to meet it's budget. <br>
<br>
what we need to do is cut the Federal government down to about 1/20 its current size, resume letting states govern themselves (which is Constitutionally legal) and stop making people pay taxes to Washington D.C. where it will just be mismanaged and lost anyway. <br>
<br>
and we should stop making people pay taxes to go to school too. i was homeschooled but that didn't prevent my parents from having to pay property taxes every year to support the local (lousy) public schools. not paying property taxes would leave everyone with more money and they could afford to go to school wherever they wanted. (well, maybe not everyone but things could be worked out without the government being heavily involved.) <br>
<br>
and i do think the rich should be taxed more than the poor. it should be a sliding scale percentage. and Bill Gates can just give a few billion dollars each year to feed Africa and then everyone will be happy. <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :p --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/images/emoticons/tongue.gif ALT=":p"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END--> <br>
<br>
enough of my rambling. <br>
